    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{r}{r^{2}+11r+30}+\frac{r}{r+6}} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{r}{r+5}, r\ne -6</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{r}{r^{2}+11r+30}+\frac{r}{r+6}} 
      \amp = {\frac{r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}+\frac{r}{r+6}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}+\frac{r}{r+6}} \cdot \frac{(r+5)}{(r+5)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}+\frac{r\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r+r\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r+r^{2}+5r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r^{2}+6r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}} \\
      \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r+6\right)}}{{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+5\right)}} \\
      \amp = {\frac{r}{r+5}, r\ne -6}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>r+6</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>r \ne {-6}</m>.</p>
</solution>
